               <p>1363. <persName id="def1-1363-18360509" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-1363-18360509" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1363-18360509" type="surname" value="HILL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1363-18360509" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">THOMAS HILL</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18360509-1363-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18360509-1363-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18360509-1363-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="stealingFromMaster"></interp> for feloniously stealing, on the <rs id="t18360509-cd-205" type="crimeDate">
                        <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18360509-1363-offence-1 t18360509-cd-205"></join>18th of September</rs>, 1 looking glass, value 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; 8 chairs, value 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; 2 pieces of floor-cloth, value 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; 2 carpets, value 5<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.; 1 pair of steps, value 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; 1 bench, value 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; 1 coal-hod, value 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; 2 cornices, value 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; 4 curtains, value 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; 1 scraper, value 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; 1 tin can, value 1<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.; 1 warming-span, value 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; 1 steak-coaster, value 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.; 1 footman, value 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; 1 candle-box, value 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.; 20 pieces of earthenware, value 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; and 1 door lock, value 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; the goods of <persName id="t18360509-name-1436" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1436" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1436" type="surname" value="CHAMBERS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1436" type="given" value="WILLIAM SURMAN"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18360509-1363-offence-1 t18360509-name-1436"></join>William Surman Chambers</persName>, in his dwelling-house.—2nd <hi rend="smallCaps">COUNT</hi>, stating them to be the goods of <persName id="t18360509-name-1437" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1437" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18360509-1363-offence-1 t18360509-name-1437"></join>William, by Divine providence, Primate of all England and Metropolitan</persName>—3rd <hi rend="smallCaps">COUNTS</hi>, of <persName id="t18360509-name-1438" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1438" type="gender" value="indeterminate"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1438" type="surname" value="HERBERT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1438" type="given" value="RICHARD CHAMBERS"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18360509-1363-offence-1 t18360509-name-1438"></join>Richard Chambers Herbert</persName>
                  </rs>.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183605090255"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18360509-name-1439" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1439" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1439" type="surname" value="WHITEHEAD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1439" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS WHITEHEAD</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a policeman. I went to the prisoner's house, on Monday, the 2nd of May, between two and three o'clock, at the request of Mr. Bedford—it is No.1, Mason-street, Lambeth—I did not take him into custody, at that time—Mr. Bedford and Mr. Barton went to get the magistrate's advice, and on their return, they gave the prisoner into custody, and about nine o'clock, I found this carpet in an upper room.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18360509-name-1440" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1440" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1440" type="surname" value="BARTON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1440" type="given" value="WILLIAM CHAMBERS"></interp>WILLIAM CHAMBERS BARTON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the natural son of the late Mr. William Surman Chambers—I was in the habit of visiting him—I lived in one of his house—he had ten houses in Whitehorse-street, Lambeth—he lived at No. 20—I was acquainted with his articles of furniture—I was at the house two or three times every day, for about twelve or eighteen months, till he went into the country, which was in July, 1834, and he died on the 17th of September following—this carpet was down in his frosst room tip-stairs, which was the room he occupied—about a month before he left, he directed me to take this carpet up, beat it, and fold it up, and put it is the black-room, on the same floor, and I did so before he left—the prisoner lodged in the lower part of the house, and paid the rent to my father—my father generally slept in the front room, and made use of the back-room as a sitting-room—he had no servant—the prisoner occupied two rooms on the ground-floor, and the kitchen—I saw him on the 6th of October following—I went into the back-room, and saw this curpet is the same place as I had placed it in before my father went into the country—I picked the key up in the front room, and the prisoner went in and unlocked the door, and I then saw the carpet there—on the 2nd of May, last, I went with Mr. Bedford to the prisoner's house, in Mason-street, and saw the carpet in an empty top room, wrapped up—we asked the prisoner to allow us permission to see what furniture he had, as we believed he had some belonging to the late Mr. Chambers—he said he had not any belonging to him—I afterwards found the carpet, which I am positive was my father's property.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PHILLIPS</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Had you lived with your father? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I lived in a house belonging to him—I never slept in my father's house—I did not visit him for about a fortnight before he left home—before that I was there two or three times a day—I had a quarrel with him about a fortnight before his death—I got into the police and left, by disobeying the orders of my superior officer—I was not discharged—I discharged myself—I would not swear that—I was removed—Mr. and Mrs. Hill were used to my father during his illness, as far as friendship went—Mrs. Hill used to go up and attend to him at times, but I used to nurse him myself.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> During the last fortnight you could not, for you were not allowed to see him? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I saw him the day he went into the country—I came to the house several times, and saw him, but was not friends with him—I do not know that Mrs. Hill was reproved for letting me in by stealth—I never heard the prisoner say that my father had made them a present of the things of their kindness to him—I never heard my father say so—I have heard the prisoner say that my father gave him the things, and he claimed there as his own.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined. Q.</hi> When did you first hear the prisoner say so? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> After my father's death—there was nobody with me then—the prisoner gave</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183605090256"></xptr>
               <p>me a silver snuff-box and spoons, and said, "These belonged to your father and I give them to you"—I said, "Very well, I will keep them for his sake," and I gave them to the administrator, Mr. Herbert—the prisoner, gave them to me at his house, No.20, White Horse-street—he said he should keep the other things that he had in his possession, and nobody should taken them—he said he considered that my father had given them to him in his waiting on my father, and kindness to him about the fortnight before I fell out with him—he did not give me any more things—the looking-glass, mahogany chairs, and window-curtains, were pun, under she prisoner care—the oil-cloth was put down in the passage in my father's dwelling house.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Was he left in charge of the things when your father went out of town? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> All the things except the carpet, which was locked up in my father's room.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PHILLIPS</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Were you present when your father delivered then things into his care? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18360509-name-1441" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1441" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1441" type="surname" value="BEDFORD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1441" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>HENRY BEDFORD</persName>
                  </hi>. I am solicitor to Mr. Herbert. He has taken out an administration to the effects of the deceased—here are the letters of administration with the will annexed, it is dated, 1827—there in no bequest to the prisoner in the will—I went with Mr. Herbert to the deceased house, in October, 1834—we were shown two rooms belonging to the de<lb></lb>ceased by Mrs. Hill—I do not think the prisoner was present—the rooms were both locked—the keys could not be found—it was supposed that the deceased had them with him—but we at last found a key which would open the front room, and in that room we found the will, and took an in<lb></lb>ventory of the things—we left the back room locked as it was—on the 9th of October we went again, the prisoner and his wife were there then—I said he had not got any key, that the deceased had got it with him, as he supposed, and we burst the door of the back room open—the key we got on the 6th was either found about the house, or Mr. Herbert had it with him, having found it in the deceased's pocket—the rooms were locked up—the prisoner did not pretend to have the control of the things at all—the carpet was not there on the 9th of October—I never saw it till the 2nd of May this year.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="largeCaps">
                     <rs id="t18360509-1363-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
